Overall, I don't think it's *too negative*, but I do think it reads a bit harsher than it probably needs to because:

* It has one short strengths section followed by a much longer development section.
* Some phrases ("behind where I would expect an SVP to be", "significant involvement", "Adam has had to remind...") can feel quite personal rather than developmental.
* A few examples are very specific and repeat the same underlying point (planning, backlog management, product knowledge).

I would keep almost everything, but soften a few sentences so they sound more like coaching than criticism. Below I've **bolded only the changes I'd make.**

---

### Opening

> Avtar joined JPMC as an SVP in January this year as technical product owner for AquaSec and VSaaS teams. Over the last six months, he's made positive contributions across our range of deliverables, made progress towards helping teams become more organised and mentoring some of the more junior members of the team. Avtar has been a positive addition to our teams and can become a key part of our wider teams. However, to do so requires some development on container security & product knowledge and being more proactive on our backlog management and sprint planning.

✅ I think this is balanced already.

---

### Overall assessment

Current:

> Despite these positive contributions across our products, I do believe Avtar is behind where I would expect an SVP to be after six months in this role. But I am confident that Avtar can get back on track by the end of the year by improving in some development areas.

I'd change to:

> Despite these positive contributions across our products, **I believe there is still scope for Avtar to continue developing towards the level I would expect from an SVP after six months in the role.** I am confident that Avtar can **make strong progress** by the end of the year by focusing on the development areas below.

**Reason:** "behind where I would expect" is quite blunt. The revised version delivers the same message without sounding like he's failing.

---

### JPMC processes

Current:

> If you're unsure on timelines or dependencies, then you can ask the team.

I'd make it:

> **If there is any uncertainty around timelines or dependencies, I would encourage Avtar to engage with the team early to help with planning.**

This feels more like coaching.

---

### Container security / product knowledge

Current:

> Adam has had to get involved to alter these updates as they're not accurate...

I'd make it:

> **Adam has provided support in refining some recent PTS monthly updates to ensure they accurately reflected the overall progress and context, and has shared feedback around the expected level of detail for future updates.**

Same point, less accusatory.

---

### Sprint planning

Current:

> Adam has also had to remind Avtar a couple of times recently...

I'd change to:

> **There have also been occasions where reminders were needed to review JIRAs within the sprint or reconsider whether they should remain sprint priorities.**

Removes the "manager correcting employee" tone while keeping the fact.

---

### Managing time

Current:

> This is currently still with the engineering leads (Adam and Ali) to help track Avtar's split...

I'd change to:

> **This currently still relies on support from the engineering leads (Adam and Ali) to help coordinate priorities across both workstreams, with an opportunity for Avtar to take greater ownership over time.**

Much more developmental.

---

### End-to-end ownership

Current:

> This is still being driven by the engineers...

I'd change to:

> **This is currently still being driven largely by the engineering team, presenting an opportunity for Avtar to take broader ownership of the end-to-end delivery process.**

---

### Vendor relationships

Current:

> This is still all being managed and driven by the engineers.

I'd change to:

> **This is currently still being managed primarily by the engineering team, with scope for Avtar to take on greater ownership of the vendor relationship and roadmap alignment.**

---

### End section

Current:

> Going into the backend of 2026...

I'd change to:

> **Going into the second half of 2026...**

("backend of 2026" doesn't sound quite right.)

---

## Overall feedback

I actually think this is a fair review. It recognises his achievements, gives concrete examples, and clearly identifies development areas.

The only sentence I'd strongly recommend changing is:

> **"I do believe Avtar is behind where I would expect an SVP to be after six months..."**

because that's the one line that is most likely to be remembered from the review. Reframing it as **"there is still scope to develop towards the level expected of an SVP"** communicates the same assessment while keeping the tone constructive. The rest mainly benefits from small wording tweaks to make it sound more like coaching than criticism.
